Halve, peel and chop the @echalion shallot{1}(peeled and chopped into ½cm pieces). Remove the root and dark green tops from the @leek{1}, cut in half lengthways and thinly slice into half moons. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}). Chop the bottom 2cm off the @asparagus{1}(trimmed, spears cut in half widthways) and discard. Pick the @basil{1}(leaves picked and stalks finely chopped) from their stalks and finely chop the stalks. Cut half of the @king prawns{250}(half of them halved widthways) in half widthways.

Boil the @water{750%ml} in a large #saucepan{} over high heat. Add the @vegetable stock pot{1}, stir to dissolve and reduce the heat to low. Put a glug of @oil{glug} in another large saucepan on medium heat. Add the shallot and leek with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and a grind of @black pepper{grind} and cook until soft, ~{5-6%minutes}. Stir in the garlic and basil stalks and cook for ~{1%minute} more.

Pour in the @risotto rice{175%g} and stir to coat in the oil. Cook for ~{1%minute}. Add the @white wine vinegar{1} and allow it to evaporate. Then add a ladleful of stock and cook, stirring, until it has been absorbed by the rice. Keep the pan on medium heat, adding stock and stirring until the rice is done, ~{20-25%minutes}. It should be soft with a hint of firmness in the middle.

> TIP: Let the rice absorb each ladleful of stock before adding another.

When the rice is almost cooked (taste to see!), stir in the halved prawns, and cook gently, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> TIP: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque all the way through.

Remove your pan from the heat. Meanwhile, heat a splash of @oil{splash} in a #frying pan{} over medium-high heat. Stir-fry the asparagus until tender, ~{4-5%minutes}. Season with @salt{pinch} and @black pepper{pinch} and transfer to a #plate{}. Keep warm, covered with #foil{}.

Leave the frying pan on the heat and stir-fry the whole prawns. Cook until pink on the outside and opaque in the centre, ~{4-5%minutes}. When done, remove from the heat and add a squeeze of @lemon{1/2}(juiced) juice. Tear the basil leaves and sprinkle half over the prawns, along with the @dukkah mix{2}.

When the risotto is cooked, add the @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g}, @Netherend butter salted{15%g} and remaining basil leaves. Stir vigorously until the butter has melted - this makes the risotto extra creamy! Taste and add more salt, black pepper and lemon juice to your liking. Spoon the risotto into #bowls{} and top it with the dukkah prawns and asparagus.